@sokket Hey, long time no see!

As @loic-sharma points out, Pulumi decouples language support from cloud providers.  For our terreaform based providers, we use [tfgen](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi-terraform/tree/master/pkg/tfgen) to generate the actual language projections, so once we have a C# backend for tfgen, we'll be able to use the Azure, GCP and AWS providers just like the other languages do.

The language run-time itself will be .NET Core.  Presently, I'm targeting netstandard2.0/netcoreapp2.0 and I hope we can keep things there to get a broad level of compatibility.

@faizans-cuelogic Yes, the arguments for this are `access_key` and `secret_key`.

This line is from the Cognito constructor:
```
if access_key and secret_key:
    self.client = boto3.client('cognito-idp',
        aws_access_key_id=access_key,
        aws_secret_access_key=secret_key,
        region_name=self.user_pool_region
        )
else:
    self.client = boto3.client('cognito-idp')
```
If you do not pass these to the constructor, boto3 looks for AWS credentials as defined in the [boto3 Credentials Configuration](https://boto3.readthedocs.io/en/latest/guide/configuration.html#configuring-credentials).

@SwartzCr asked me to respond to this.

@r5d, the problematic functions are `certbot.main.make_or_verify_needed_dirs` (as you correctly pointed out) and `certbot.log.post_arg_parse_setup`.

As for how to accomplish this, it might be simplest to just do something like:
```
try:
    log.post_arg_parse_setup(config)
    make_or_verify_needed_dirs(config)
except errors.Error:
    if config.func != plugins_cmd:
        raise
```
While this feels a little hacky, the "plugins" subcommand is the exception here so moving this code into the other individual subcommands seems like a recipe for bugs when new subcommands are added in the future. Additionally, I think we should always try to run this code because when it's not run successfully, logs are written to a temporary file instead of the normal log directory. We should try to run it for the times when we do have the necessary permissions.

I'm open to other ideas if you have them though.

